Note:
@Reasoning
SYS_FSYNC returns the platform-specific fsync(2) syscall number.
fsync flushes the in-core state of an open file descriptor to the
underlying storage device. console_primitive.console_flush_stdout
and console_flush_stderr depend on this dispatcher entry to obtain
the correct number for the active backend before invoking syscall_1.

Per-platform numbers cited from authoritative kernel headers:
  - Linux x86_64:  74  (arch/x86/entry/syscalls/syscall_64.tbl)
  - Linux ARM64:   82  (include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h)
  - Linux ARM32:  118  (arch/arm/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h, OABI)
  - MIPS32:      4118  (Linux MIPS o32 ABI, 4000-base)
  - MIPS64:      5072  (Linux MIPS n64 ABI, 5000-base)
  - Darwin x64/ARM64:  95  (bsd/kern/syscalls.master)
  - FreeBSD x64/ARM64: 95  (sys/sys/syscall.h)
  - NetBSD x64/ARM64:  95  (sys/sys/syscall.h)
  - OpenBSD x64/ARM64: 95  (sys/sys/syscall.h)
  - Windows x64/ARM64: -1 sentinel (no direct Win32 equivalent;
    fsync is emulated through the FlushFileBuffers Win32 API in
    the platform's higher-level wrappers, not via raw syscall)
  - PowerPC:    118  (Linux PowerPC unistd.h)
  - RISC-V 32:   82  (asm-generic unistd.h)
  - RISC-V 64:   82  (asm-generic unistd.h)
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Pure dispatch table: read backend index via _ensure_backend_selected,
then return the platform-prefixed constant. No state mutation, no
side effects, no allocation. Final-line fallback returns the
linux_x86_64 number so an unrecognised backend behaves like the
default-Linux path used elsewhere in this dispatcher.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One indirect call + at most 18 integer compares + one constant
return. The compiler may inline the platform constant once the
backend is selected at startup. Hot-path callers (e.g. flush)
should cache the returned number if it is consulted repeatedly,
but the cost of an extra call is negligible compared with the
kernel transition that follows.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
This proc returns a kernel-ABI constant only. It performs no I/O,
opens no file descriptors, and touches no user-controlled memory.
The returned integer is consumed by syscall_1/syscall_3 which DO
cross the kernel boundary; callers are responsible for validating
the file descriptor argument they pass to fsync.
@End Security_Scope
:End Note

Process called "SYS_FSYNC" returns Integer:
    Let idx be proc _ensure_backend_selected
    If idx is equal to 1: Return proc linux_x86_64_SYS_FSYNC from LinuxX86_64 End If
    If idx is equal to 2: Return proc linux_arm64_SYS_FSYNC from LinuxARM64 End If
    If idx is equal to 3: Return proc linux_arm32_SYS_FSYNC from LinuxARM32 End If
    If idx is equal to 4: Return proc mips32_SYS_FSYNC from MIPS32 End If
    If idx is equal to 5: Return proc mips64_SYS_FSYNC from MIPS64 End If
    If idx is equal to 6: Return proc darwin_x86_64_SYS_FSYNC from DarwinX86_64 End If
    If idx is equal to 7: Return proc darwin_arm64_SYS_FSYNC from DarwinARM64 End If
    If idx is equal to 8: Return proc freebsd_x64_SYS_FSYNC from FreeBSDX64 End If
    If idx is equal to 9: Return proc freebsd_arm64_SYS_FSYNC from FreeBSDARM64 End If
    If idx is equal to 10: Return proc netbsd_x64_SYS_FSYNC from NetBSDX64 End If
    If idx is equal to 11: Return proc netbsd_arm64_SYS_FSYNC from NetBSDARM64 End If
    If idx is equal to 12: Return proc openbsd_x64_SYS_FSYNC from OpenBSDX64 End If
    If idx is equal to 13: Return proc openbsd_arm64_SYS_FSYNC from OpenBSDARM64 End If
    If idx is equal to 14: Return proc windows_x86_64_SYS_FSYNC from WindowsX86_64 End If
    If idx is equal to 15: Return proc windows_arm64_SYS_FSYNC from WindowsARM64 End If
    If idx is equal to 16: Return proc powerpc_SYS_FSYNC from PowerPC End If
    If idx is equal to 17: Return proc riscv32_SYS_FSYNC from RISCV32 End If
    If idx is equal to 18: Return proc riscv64_SYS_FSYNC from RISCV64 End If
    Return proc linux_x86_64_SYS_FSYNC from LinuxX86_64
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
PROCESS/USER INTROSPECTION SYSCALLS
============================================================================
Per-platform syscall numbers for getpid, getppid, getuid/gid (real),
geteuid/egid (effective). Each platform file exports the platform-
specific number; the router dispatches based on the active backend.
Darwin and Windows expose these through different mechanisms (Mach IPC
on Darwin, GetCurrentProcessId/etc on Windows); their platform/syscall.runa
files convert those to the same Integer-returning Process shape so this
dispatcher works uniformly.
:End Note

