Note:
@Reasoning
syscall_ioctl issues a device-specific I/O control request on an open
file descriptor. console_primitive.console_is_tty uses TCGETS, and
console_get_terminal_size uses TIOCGWINSZ. Both call into this typed
wrapper rather than computing the syscall number themselves, so the
dispatcher must expose ioctl as a first-class entry parallel to
syscall_read / syscall_write / syscall_lseek.

The wrapper takes (fd, cmd, arg) where cmd is the ioctl request code
(TCGETS, TIOCGWINSZ, FIONREAD, ...) and arg is either an integer or a
pointer to a request-specific data structure.

Windows backends route to DeviceIoControl through their own platform
wrappers; the Win32 path is owned by the Windows backend's
syscall_ioctl proc which translates Unix-style request codes to the
nearest Win32 CTL_CODE-encoded IOCTL or returns a -1 sentinel for
unsupported requests (callers must treat negative returns as errors).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Pure dispatch table — read backend index via _ensure_backend_selected,
forward (fd, cmd, arg) to the platform-prefixed ioctl wrapper. Each
platform wrapper composes the platform-specific SYS_IOCTL constant
with syscall_3 (passing fd, cmd, arg). Final-line fallback returns
-1 for an unrecognised backend, matching the error convention of the
other typed syscall wrappers in this dispatcher.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single indirect call + at most 18 integer compares + tail-call to the
platform wrapper. The platform wrapper compiles to one constant load
plus the kernel transition. Because ioctl is request-defined, callers
are responsible for batching: do not invoke this for every byte of a
serial buffer when FIONREAD can report the queue depth in one call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
syscall_ioctl crosses the kernel boundary with caller-supplied fd,
cmd, and arg. The argp pointer (if non-zero) is dereferenced by the
kernel for the request-specific structure size, so callers MUST:
  (1) own the fd (no UAF, no negative descriptors),
  (2) size the buffer to match the request (e.g. struct termios for
      TCGETS, struct winsize for TIOCGWINSZ),
  (3) treat negative return values as failure (errno semantics).
This dispatcher performs no validation — it is a thin routing layer.
The platform wrappers and the kernel enforce all safety properties.
@End Security_Scope
:End Note

